				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$_{in}$$\end{document}, have developed, above and below the high pressure beam heated tungsten region. The former shock moves radially outwards, whereas the latter propagates inwards. It is also seen that the inmoving shock is relatively weaker because the pusher is preheated by the wings of the Gaussian distribution represented by A = 0.2, in the present case. The figure also shows rarefaction waves penetrating into the target from both faces and significant material expansion has taken place.

